Taiwan Stocks: Asustek, Formosa Plastics, HTC, Powertech, Wintek

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-08-02T05:46:03Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-02/china-steel-far-eastern-formosa-hon-hai-taiwan-stock-preview.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in Taiwan trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 1:30 p.m. close in Taipei.  The Taiex Index fell 116.66, or 1.3 percent, to 8,584.72.  Asustek Computer Inc. (2357)  (2357 TT) climbed 6.5 percent to
NT$264, the highest close since Jan. 18, 2010. The computer
maker’s long-term foreign and local-currency issuer default
ratings were upgraded to BBB from BB+ at  Fitch Ratings , which
cited the company’s increasing market share and improved
financial profile.  Formosa Petrochemical Corp. (6505)  (6505 TT) retreated for a
second day, sliding 6.9 percent to NT$94. Taiwan’s only publicly
traded oil refiner suspended export obligations on oil products
from its Mailiao processing plant indefinitely following a fire
at the site.  Other Formosa Plastics Group units also fell.  Formosa
Plastics Corp. (1301)  (1301 TT) tumbled 6.9 percent to NT$94.  Formosa
Chemicals & Fibre Corp. (1326)  (1326 TT) slumped 7 percent to NT$90.40.
 Nan Ya Plastics Corp. (1303)  (1303 TT) declined 5.7 percent to NT$70.  HTC Corp. (2498)  (2498 TT), the world’s largest maker of handsets
using operating systems from Google Inc., gained 4.4 percent to
NT$898 after research company Canalys said Google’s Android was
the biggest smartphone operating system by global shipments in
the second quarter.  Powertech Technology Inc. (6239)  (6239 TT) lost 5.5 percent to
NT$75.50, the lowest close since Aug. 6, 2009, after Goldman
Sachs Group Inc. cut its share-price estimate to NT$100 from
NT$109. The provider of chip testing services has dropped for
three straight days since it reported on July 28 after the close
of the island’s stock market a decline in second-quarter profit.
Goldman Sachs kept its “buy” rating on the company.  Wintek Corp. (2384)  (2384 TT) jumped 6.9 percent to NT$37, the
biggest advance since July 14, on speculation it got additional
touch panel orders for Apple Inc.’s iPad and Amazon.com Inc.’s
new tablet computer, said Calvin Shao, an analyst at SinoPac
Securities Corp. Jay Huang, a spokesman for Wintek, wasn’t
immediately available for comment at his office.  To contact the reporter on this story:
